@GarlicAvenger I disagree, and if I dare, think it’s approaching misunderstanding, assumption, or even slander to say he hated Dwarves. I’ve often personally felt his “never toss a Dwarf” insertion in Fellowship was a frown to the Australian Dwarf Tossing bar scene in the 80’s. Jackson being a Kiwi, it makes sense, and it comes full circle in Two Towers when Gimli overcomes that—much like the unexplained love of Gimli for Legolas after the Extended Editions show the gift of Galadriel’s hair, and how Legolas immediately accepts and befriends Gimli. 
If you’re talking about turning the key Dwarf character to comic relief, I could agree. But as you said, it’s a great production as a whole, and honors the themes and heart of Tolkien overall. 
I’ve also considered the quote of Gimli at the Black Gate in the films, admitting friendship to Legolas, as some decent development and serious relief from that comic dialogue too.

@GarlicAvenger  Hating the Dwarfs or been a elf simp doesn't mean he wasn't a fan. It's like saying someone hate a sport because they hate the team they are against it, and favors theirs.  And he might have taken a lot of creative liberties, some which I don't agree and couple I hate. But there is no denying that he at least had great respect for Tolkien. While he had to make good Movies. I could sit through a 1:1 book to movie adaptation. But vast majority of people wouldn't. 
Plus all the tings missing. Some people already considered the theatrical versions long, let along the extended cut. No way they could add everything and be able to flush out the characters, locations and lore as they did. They'd need 2 movies at least per book and like 3 for the last. Not something possible, specially at the time.
To be honest, we were lucky we got those movies when we got them.

