@rikhuravidansker Not so sure about part of Herefordshire becoming part of the Metropolitan County of the West Midlands. Parts of Staffordshire and Worcestershire did, as well as parts of Warwickshire I think, but Worcs is between Herefordshire and the West Midlands.  Perhaps the reference was made before Herefordshire and Worcs separated in the 90s (I think), when Hereford and Worcs was one county.
With West Midlands (the region composed of counties, rather than the metropolitan county) English, it's peculiar in that it can vary from person to person even in the same village.  For example my cousin in a village in Southern Shropshire has more of a rural accent, whilst his wife has more of a West Mids (county) accent...perhaps because she grew up in Kidderminster; however there are older people in Kidderminster who have more of a rural accent, whereas the younger people almost all have a West Mids/Brummie type accent.  The spread of Estuary English is documented, and I've noticed that people from Cambridge and Peterborough have south eastern accents; yet the accent in a recording I listened to made in the 70s of a bloke from Cambs in his 90s (so born 1880s) was much more rural than the people you hear from there now.
It's been said that Black Country dialect is the closest to old (Anglo Saxon) English and there are indeed some archaisms which are very close to modern German such as ''ow bist?'' for how are you, or housen instead of houses for the plural.  However Black Country isn't one dialect or accent and people at least used to know someone was from a place 3 or 4 miles away by their different accent, e.g. Sedgely vs Gornal, etc.

